{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487035"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:54:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0,0.13,0.09,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/237"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"6562"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44567"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a nine hour history of right sided headache with dull neck pain on the same side. The pain is increasing in severity and he has never had a headache or neck pain like this before. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not drink alcohol. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 136/90mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His eyes have this appearance when he is instructed to look straight ahead (Image). The neurological examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis in this setting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT angiogram carotid/circle of Willis","Electrocardiography","Carotid duplex ultrasound","Chest X-ray","MR head, neck and chest"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows Horner\u0027s syndrome (miosis and partial ptosis +/- anhidrosis). Horner\u0027s syndrome results from a lack of sympathetic stimulation, which can be caused by injury or compression anywhere along the sympathetic chain. Clinical signs are ipsilateral to the side of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has Horner\u0027s syndrome affecting the right side, associated with a right-sided headache and neck pain. This clinical picture is consistent with a diagnosis of carotid artery dissection. Pre contrast CT of the neck would not be routine or required in the assessment of carotid dissection. In day to day practice a non contrast CT brain would be usually be performed beforehand to assess for intracranial sequelae of dissection (stroke, haemorrhage) which can be more difficult to assess on arterial phase imaging. This is contrasted with imaging for acute aortic syndromes/aortic dissection where a non contrast CT of the chest is routinely performed to assess for aortic intramural haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid/circle of Willis \u003C/strong\u003Eis highly sensitive and specific for diagnosing carotid dissection and is an appropriate imaging modality in the emergency setting, given its availability and speed of image acquisition. The lung apices are usually completely captured on this form of imaging and thus may also assist in exclusion of other causes of Horner\u2019s syndrome e.g. Pancoast tumour, as well as the presence of aortic dissection, which may be associated with this pathology. Potential drawbacks of this form of imaging include radiation exposure as well as requirement for iodinated contrast.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is an inexpensive, safe, portable imaging modality and can be performed at the bedside in the Emergency Department, and is a useful investigation in the initial evaluation of carotid dissection. However, a multimodal imaging approach is often required; and the diagnosis is usually confirmed thereafter with CT angiogram or MR angiogram. Further to this, there is evidence to suggest that the sensitivity of carotid duplex ultrasound is reduced in the setting of ipsilateral Horner\u2019s syndrome; or where the dissection arises near the base of skull.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E MR head, neck and chest\u003C/strong\u003E could be used to detect a number of causes for Horner\u0027s syndrome. However, MR with angiogram phase is preferred for visualising a dissection. While MR angiogram is the most sensitive non-invasive imaging modality for diagnosis of carotid dissection, it is often less widely available than the aforementioned investigations, and the lower speed of image acquisition may hinder the establishment of a timely diagnosis in the emergency setting. This is of particular concern where the patient also presents with associated neurological complications (i.e. ischaemic stroke).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to look for a Pancoast tumour, a rare carcinoma of the lung apex that can cause compression of the sympathetic chain. However, this would not be expected to cause a headache or neck pain. The lung apices are usually completely captured on a carotid/circle of Willis CT angiogram and a Pancoast tumour should be able to be seen without the need for separate imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERarely, Horner\u0027s syndrome may be caused by lateral medullary syndrome secondary to ischaemia. In any stroke, \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrocardiogram (ECG)\u003C/strong\u003E should be used to look for atrial fibrillation as a cause. However, diagnosing the stroke with CT brain or MRI would be the first step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Horner\u0027s syndrome can be caused by injury anywhere along the sympathetic chain"],"references":["Hakimi R, Sivakumar S. Imaging of Carotid Dissection. Curr Pain Headache Rep. 2019;23(1):2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30661121/","Dittrich R, Ritter MA, Ringelstein EB. Ultrasound in spontaneous cervical artery dissection. Perspect Med. 2012;1(1):250-4. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2211968X12000319"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29297"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"13789"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"13789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/13789"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/04aca91e-34fb-4371-8e5f-0f0e4cbd488a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/04aca91e-34fb-4371-8e5f-0f0e4cbd488a.jpg","isProcessed":tr